    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>You'll want a <code>Map&lt;String, String&gt;</code>. Classes that implement the <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/Map.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><code>Map</code></a> interface include (but are not limited to):</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/HashMap.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><code>HashMap</code></a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/LinkedHashMap.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><code>LinkedHashMap</code></a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/Hashtable.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><code>Hashtable</code></a></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Each is designed/optimized for certain situations (go to their respective docs for more info). <code>HashMap</code> is probably the most common; the go-to default.</p>\n\n<p>For example (using a <code>HashMap</code>):</p>\n\n<pre><code>Map&lt;String, String&gt; map = new HashMap&lt;String, String&gt;();\nmap.put(\"dog\", \"type of animal\");\nSystem.out.println(map.get(\"dog\"));\n</code></pre>\n\n<pre>\ntype of animal\n</pre>\n"
  } ],
